### [1 Corinthians Chapter 12](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#001.md)

[1 Corinthians 12:1](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#001.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_001">co1 12:1</span></span>

spiritual gifts

The Greek word, "pneumatika", literally means, "spirituals", that is,
matters of or from the Holy Spirit, gives the key to Chapters 12, 13,
14. Chapter 12 concerns the Spirit in relation to the body of Christ.
This relation is twofold:

\(1\) The baptism with the Spirit forms the body by uniting believers to
Christ the risen and glorified Head, and to each other ([Co1
12:12](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#012).md); ([Co1
12:13](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#013).md). The symbol of the body thus
formed is the natural, human body ([Co1
12:12](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#012).md), and all the analogies are
freely used ([Co1 12:14-26](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#014).md).

\(2\) To each believer is given a spiritual enablement and capacity for
specific service. No believer is destitute of such gift ([Co1
12:7](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#007).md); ([Co1
12:11](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#011).md); ([Co1
12:27](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#027).md), but in their distribution the
Spirit acts in free sovereignty ([Co1
12:11](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#011).md). There is no room for
self-choosing, and Christian service is simply the ministry of such gift
as the individual may have received (cf) ([Rom
12:4-8](../../../bib/kjv/rom012.htm#004).md). The gifts are diverse ([Co1
12:6](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#006).md); ([Co1
12:8-10](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#008).md); ([Co1
12:28-30](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#028).md), but all are equally
honourable because bestowed by the same Spirit, administered under the
same Lord, and energized by the same God.

[1 Corinthians 12:4](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#004.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_004">co1 12:4</span></span>

gifts

Compare ([Eph 4:8](../../../bib/kjv/eph004.htm#008).md); ([Eph
4:11](../../../bib/kjv/eph004.htm#011).md); ([Eph
4:12](../../../bib/kjv/eph004.htm#012).md).

The Spirit gives gifts for service to men, Christ gives the gifted men
to the churches.

[1 Corinthians 12:10](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#010.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_010">co1 12:10</span></span>

prophecy

The New Testament prophet is not ordinarily a foreteller, but rather a
forth-teller, one whose gift enabled him to speak "to edification, and
exhortation, and comfort" ([Co1 14:3](../../../bib/kjv/co1014.htm#003).md).

[1 Corinthians 12:31](../../../bib/kjv/co1012.htm#031.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_031">co1 12:31</span></span>

more excellent

Chapter 13 continues the pneumatika begun in Chapter 12.

Gifts are good, but only if ministered in love. ([Co1
13:1](../../../bib/kjv/co1013.htm#001).md); ([Co1
13:2](../../../bib/kjv/co1013.htm#002).md).

Benevolence is good, but not apart from love. ([Co1
13:3](../../../bib/kjv/co1013.htm#003).md).

Love is described. ([Co1 13:4-7](../../../bib/kjv/co1013.htm#004).md).

Love is better than our present incomplete knowledge, ([Co1
13:8-12](../../../bib/kjv/co1013.htm#008).md),

and greater than even faith and hope ([Co1
13:13](../../../bib/kjv/co1013.htm#013).md).

